      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here is the paper you're looking for:\n\n## **Grokking as Compression: A Nonlinear Complexity Perspective**\n**arXiv: 2310.05918**\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "**Authors:** Ziming Liu (MIT & IAIFI), Ziqian Zhong (MIT), and Max Tegmark (MIT & IAIFI)."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "This paper was presented at the **NeurIPS 2023 UniReps workshop**."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Summary\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The paper attributes grokking — the phenomenon where generalization is much delayed after memorization — to compression."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "To do so, the authors define **linear mapping number (LMN)** to measure network complexity, which is a generalized version of linear region number for ReLU networks."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\nThe authors argue LMN is superior to the L₂ norm for characterizing model complexity for several reasons:\n\n1. "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "LMN can be naturally interpreted as information/computation, while L₂ cannot."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n2. "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "In the compression phase, LMN has linear relations with test losses, while L₂ is correlated with test losses in a complicated nonlinear way."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n3. "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "LMN also reveals an intriguing phenomenon of the XOR network switching between two generalization solutions, while L₂ does not."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The authors use LMN to characterize the compression process of grokking on three algorithmic tasks: modular addition, permutation group S₄, and multi-digit XOR."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "After memorization and before generalization, the LMN decreases steadily and has a strong linear relation with test loss."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "They also argue that LMN is a promising candidate as the neural network version of the Kolmogorov complexity since it explicitly considers local or conditioned linear computations aligned with the nature of modern artificial neural networks."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**Link:** [https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.05918](https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.05918)"
      }
    ],
